WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.800
We present Gelsphere: an Omni-directional rolling vision-based Tectile sensor

00:03.960 --> 00:07.300
for online 3D reconstruction and normal force estimation.

00:07.400 --> 00:10.000
This sensor overcomes the previous sensor's limitations,

00:10.100 --> 00:12.300
such as the inability to perform continuous scanning,

00:12.400 --> 00:15.000
or having only one axis for the scanning direction.

00:15.560 --> 00:18.400
Surface inspection is important in manufacturing and maintenance,

00:18.520 --> 00:23.800
especially for large parts like aircraft skins, pipes, molds, and composite panels.

00:23.960 --> 00:25.700
Vision-based inspection can be fast,

00:25.840 --> 00:28.160
but it is often limited by glare, occlusion,

00:28.320 --> 00:29.960
and curved or confined geometry.

00:30.880 --> 00:32.900
Tactile sensing solves some of these issues

00:33.000 --> 00:35.000
because it measures surface to contact,

00:35.100 --> 00:37.800
but most tactile sensors only capture a small patch at a time,

00:38.120 --> 00:40.320
so scanning large areas become slow

00:40.320 --> 00:42.440
and requires repeated press and lift motion.

00:43.720 --> 00:47.400
Mechanically, gel sphere is inspired by a ball transfer unit.

00:47.920 --> 00:49.500
A layer of miniature steel balls form

00:49.680 --> 00:52.600
a low friction bearing between the sensor gel pad and the housing.

00:53.440 --> 00:55.000
This allows smooth rolling motion

00:55.100 --> 00:57.000
and continuous contact during scanning.

00:57.880 --> 00:59.440
The sensor is entirely self-contained

00:59.440 --> 01:01.520
with a compact camera module with Wi-Fi,

01:01.880 --> 01:05.200
an RGB LED ring, and a battery on a lightweight base.

01:06.160 --> 01:08.400
The internal base is magnetically suspended,

01:08.500 --> 01:11.000
which helps keeps the camera pointed toward the sensing surface

01:11.120 --> 01:13.500
even as the outer gel rolls and changes orientation.

01:14.640 --> 01:16.600
We also integrate a magnetic switch,

01:16.700 --> 01:19.400
so we can turn the sensor on and off without opening the housing.

01:20.560 --> 01:22.700
We build and test the sensor in two different coatings,

01:22.800 --> 01:25.120
specular and matte, and compare their performances.

01:26.520 --> 01:28.600
Here is a real-time reconstruction on a surface.

01:29.200 --> 01:30.900
We estimate frame to frame motion,

01:31.320 --> 01:32.800
align consecutive tactile frames,

01:32.800 --> 01:35.900
and fuse them online to provide immediate feedback during scanning.

01:36.640 --> 01:38.800
Because gel sphere rolls omnidirectionally,

01:38.900 --> 01:41.700
the scan path does not need to follow one fixed axis,

01:41.960 --> 01:44.700
so the sensor can handle curved and irregular trajectories.

01:46.200 --> 01:48.500
After scanning, we run an offline reconstruction,

01:48.600 --> 01:51.200
which allows higher quality stitching and integration.

01:52.080 --> 01:54.200
The result is a stitch surface and a mesh

01:54.240 --> 01:57.000
that covers a much larger area than a single contact frame.

01:58.160 --> 02:01.300
Gel sphere also estimates normal force directly from tactile images.

02:02.000 --> 02:04.700
When force increases, the contact patch grows,

02:04.800 --> 02:07.100
and the deformation pattern changes in a consistent way.

02:08.000 --> 02:09.680
Using synchronized force measurements,

02:09.960 --> 02:13.400
we train a model that maps corresponding tactile image to normal force.

02:14.560 --> 02:18.700
In our data set, the specular coating achieves 0.44 N MAE,

02:18.960 --> 02:21.900
and the matte coating achieves 0.93 N MAE.

02:22.320 --> 02:25.800
This difference shows that specular coding demonstrates higher accuracy,

02:26.000 --> 02:27.880
because higher contrast in textile image

02:27.880 --> 02:31.000
improves both geometry reconstruction and force estimation.

02:32.400 --> 02:36.200
Overall, Gelsphere maintains continuous contact while rolling in any direction.

02:36.800 --> 02:39.000
It supports real-time reconstruction for scanning feedback,

02:39.100 --> 02:42.400
and produces high-quality offline reconstruction after data collection.

02:43.320 --> 02:46.400
It also provides contact force estimation from tactile images.

02:47.680 --> 02:49.800
The Gelsphere can be used in various applications,

02:49.900 --> 02:51.300
can be human operated

02:51.400 --> 02:54.200
or mounted on robotic systems for automated surface scanning.

02:54.960 --> 02:58.000
The potential use can include inspection of large curved structures

02:58.100 --> 03:00.160
or detection of surface defects.
